Description.LocalizedString: She'd seen things growing up on Jackson's Star, things darker than the eternal night that engulfs it.
The space station Renaissance was filled with shadowy, menacing corners, but Rain's determination to help her friends gave her the courage to press on.
Shrugging off her fatigue, she dug down into new reserves of stamina and kept running.
They shared the outfit's color scheme ahead of time so she could find hair dye that matched.
The clothes were covered in LED panels that dazzled the eye. The effect even looked 3D in some places.
The company put their mascot on the legwarmers, a cute little cherry on top of the whole ensemble.
He slept in that morning, still sad that the movie was officially canceled.
He had been so excited to bring his favorite video game to the silver screen.
He dressed for a long, quiet day by the pool, flipping through a stack of scripts, knowing none of them would be as exciting as Reign of Kaiju.
Tentacles hung from the corpse's mouth, still slithering even as the creature suffocated in the open air.
The body was waterlogged, and Talbot thought he saw tiny creatures swimming just beneath the skin.
The potential for true genetic symbiosis sparked his imagination, a being neither human nor sea-creature, but something so much more.
He grabbed a dead crab half-buried in the sand. The shell was cracked, and he used it to slice his neighbor's throat open.
The sand turned to black mud and the sight of what emerged made him cry out in terrified elation.
He closed his eyes and spread his arms, ready to receive whatever fate would befall him.
His hands explored his face, and the strange mask that was suddenly wearing.
His heart was racing. He could remember putting on this costume. What did it all mean?
There were screams and roars coming from all around him. And they were getting closer.
It felt cold against her skin, like the final caress of death.
She was fascinated by the hands in front of her, and the skull they were holding.
Something was approaching, and her instincts told her to run.
She couldn't recognize the materials used to make her mask, and wondered how it came to be.
A man wearing the same outfit crawled towards her, bleeding. The chill returned as she realized they were wearing a uniform.
She bent down to help to bleeding man when she heard something in the distance running towards them.
He could barely see out of one eye, his hands running over the red crystal that was fused to his mask.
He felt a round plate pressing into his back. His fingers fumbled around the edges, trying to decipher the strange etchings.
Whatever the meaning behind these clothes, he understood immediately the danger he was in.
She was caught off-guard by the mask on her face. Where did it come from?
She'd never seen anyone wear anything like this. Where did these clothes come from?
She didn't know which way to run. The footsteps were coming from her left and right.
The mask fit her face perfectly. She knew enough about cosplay to know how hard that was to do.
The costume reminded her of a game she had played long ago. Perhaps this was a different kind of game?
Suddenly a group of people all wearing the same costume ran past. She didn't think twice about following them.
The metallic mask felt finely made, luxurious and menacing in equal measure.
How did she come to be dressed in such ornate clothing? And how was it a perfect fit?
This was no time to admire her new outfit. She could sense a different kind of danger lurking nearby.
He could see a multitude of colors in his peripheral vision, only realizing a moment later that he was wearing a mask.
David knew a uniform when he saw one, and this one fit him perfectly.
In front of him was a group of people dressed just like him, repairing a broken generator.
He felt the spikes protruding from his helmet, ignoring the pain as he sliced open a fingertip.
He heard movement nearby, and his desire for bloodshed ignited.
He expected to find a sacrifice waiting for him, but was surprised when he locked eyes with a kindred spirit instead.
He wished he could see how fearsome he looked in this strange new mask.
He didn't question the clothes he was wearing. He knew it was all for a higher purpose.
He revved his chainsaw, wondering when he'd meet his new friend.
He stood before a sinister figure in a spiky red mask, and quickly realized he was wearing a similar mask.
Whoever this was, they were here for a similar purpose. A voice inside told him they would have to work together.
Together they forged ahead, their connection strong and unspoken.
She could see without seeing and was taken aback by her own appearance.
She never imagined such finery could ever exist, much less be made for her to wear.
The screams of past patients rang in her ears as she readied her latest instrument of pain.
She imagined stalking the forests of her homeland, menacing the invaders with this blood-red mask.
A worthy sacrifice suddenly ran by, and she quickly pulled out a hatchet.
As she swung her axe, a figure emerged from out of sight. Not another sacrifice, but someone different altogether.
She believed the speakeasy in the basement was an Overlap, a place where two dimensions intersected.
She found a spectral man standing behind the bar, trying to open a moldy barrel, a large gaping hole in his back.
The man turned around and reached for Haddie. She fought back a scream and ran up the stairs.
It was this book's protagonist who made him want to be an agent when he was a young boy.
Reading the book as an adult was a different experience altogether. The hero spy was an expert in fieldwork, able to get out of any situation.
After everything he'd been through, Jonah still felt like a number-cruncher. He would never be as cool or capable as the hero who inspired him.
The detective on the screen was funny, clever, and impeccably dressed. Jane watched her every move with admiration.
At last came the detective's death scene. Jane reached for a pack of tissues, sad but also thankful to have gone on such an emotional journey.
The credits rolled and Jane left the theater feeling inspired. One day, she would connect with people the way the detective connected with her.
A heavily altered welding mask. Bloodstained and terrifying.
She wished for the power to defend herself. She wished for something more.
The snake emerged from the darkness, tearing into her father with its razor-sharp fangs.
She awoke in a sweat, fearing the day as much as she did the night.
She felt the violence within her own self, and feared she'd become as monstrous as her father.
She never understood why rescue came in the form of a snake, but there it was, bearing its fangs.
She awoke screaming, knowing the day would bring its own dangers.
Some saw the creature as a nuisance, but Yui's grandmother knew better than that.
It was the lowest point in her life, and she needed all the guidance she could get.
The fox scampered through the trees, and Yui knew she had to follow.
Her grandmother had seen the same creature in these woods so many years ago.
She was leaving her hometown for the last time, adrift and in need of guidance.
She watched the fox scamper into the forest and left her bike out on the road.
The open window was the only clue, and she saw something moving in the alley below.
She climbed down the fire escape, moving quietly to avoid detection.
She found the Bengal cat in the alley. It looked up at her and ran away, leaving the artifact behind.
Huddled in his bunker, he waited for a sign that it was safe to come out of hiding.
The lizard came to him in the night, and he knew it was the sign he was waiting for.
Everything would be all right from now on, and his grandmother would always be with him.
He didn't feel much like a lion, but he didn't want to let his team down.
He had the ball and the goal line was in sight when he saw a lion running alongside him.
He leapt through the air and brought his prey crashing down to the ground.
The gargoyles watched over the dead, and Sable begged their pardon as she passed by.
She couldn't help but wonder what it would be like to be laid to rest here, and when it would happen.
She hoped the gargoyles would watch over her too, when her time came.
She felt the eyes of the gargoyles on her and gave them a respectful curtsey.
Thoughts of her inevitable death flooded her mind as she found an empty plot.
She lay at the bottom of the hole and asked the gargoyles to watch over her.
He would stare at the ape for hours, imagining all the ways he could make it disappear.
The orangutan spoke to him telepathically, and his heart stopped in his chest.
The orangutan told him to be nicer to the animals, especially Maurice. He backed away, trying not to run.
He couldn't believe his eyes. In his mother's stories, the purple rooster watched over the family and would always protect him.
He reached out to touch the rooster, only to watch it disappear in the burning mass.
Later that night, he listened back to the recording. The screams were there, and so were the screeches.
It was the same creature from his mother's stories, and for a moment he felt like a kid again.
The rooster vanished into the flames, and the power it held over him was broken.
It was his favorite recording, a beautiful melody formed of screams and crows.
The challenger unsheathed his sword, ready to strike down a defenseless lord.
The silver wolf lunged from the trees, its sharp teeth bared at the challenger.
Blood stained the soil, and Vittorio watched in astonishment as the wolf disappeared once again.

She decided something had to be done. If she couldn't sleep, then neither could Renato.
She grabbed the ice bucket from the table and threw the melted water on Renato, laughing as he woke up in a flurry.
Her laughter echoed down the hallway as she ran to the front door, and the beach that lay on the other side.
He hid behind the front door, waiting for her to come home. The thought of scaring her made him laugh hard.
She entered the apartment, and he jumped out at her. She screamed and punched him hard in the nose.
His legs went wobbly. In the sudden haze, he could hear Thalita apologizing profusely as she brought him to the bathroom.
He stumbled into the convenience store, unsure what to do next. He massaged his temples – bright fluorescent lights always brought on headaches.
He found some loose coins in his back pocket and counted them in front of the cashier. It was just enough to buy a scratch-off.
He scratched at the ticket with his fingernail. He suddenly slammed the ticket down on the counter and let out a triumphant whoop. Luck was back on his side.
Kate held out the guitar, offering it to the little girl. Her face lit up and she nodded eagerly.
Kate gave the girl a pick and showed her how to form an E-minor chord. The girl giggled as she ran the pick across the strings.
They sat in the park for almost an hour. When it was time to go home, the girl's mother thanked Kate for making their day.
He winced in pain as he struggled to stand up. His ears rang, and eyes stung from dust before another punch struck.
Drenched in sweat, he retreated to his workshop. Rage consumed him, feeding his mind with sketches and plans.
He pictured the brutes begging for mercy as blades cut through their bodies. They would die wishing they'd never crossed the Deathslinger.
He examined what became of his body, processing the many alterations his form could take.
There was always more blood to shed, and so many modifications he could make.
He would demonstrate his superiority, one victim at a time.
His sight grew hazy as he listened to the voice humming in his mind—constant, taunting.
Torn bodies dangled from branches above him. Their blood dripped over him in a steady rhythm.
He stared up at the trees and reveled in his work. All was silent once again.
